00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:59.200
now i've heard this from both designers
and clients

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:02.720
in fact for an email design project
where a client wanted the color scheme

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:05.519
to be accessible
they initially sent us the color codes

00:04:05.519 --> 00:04:09.200
for only their darker brand colors
which we didn't find out about until the

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:13.599
middle of the project
now here's an accessible website i

00:04:13.599 --> 00:04:18.320
designed and built several years ago
it isn't ugly and it doesn't use dark

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:22.079
colors
and here's an example of using dark

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:25.600
colors together that i found while
shopping online

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:30.320
people without vision issues would have
a hard time reading this i certainly did

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:35.680
it always depends on how the colors are
used together as i'll get into

00:04:35.680 --> 00:04:40.080
some designers and developers and their
clients think that accessibility only

00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:45.360
applies to a small population
or only to older people

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:52.479
but worldwide it is estimated that 2.2
billion people have a visual disability

00:04:53.120 --> 00:04:57.759
one of those could be low vision and low
vision is having best corrected visual

00:04:57.759 --> 00:05:01.199
acuity
at less than 20 40 in the better seeing

00:05:01.199 --> 00:05:04.080
eye
and this can be due to macular

00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:08.840
degeneration
cataract diabetic retinopathy or

00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:13.520
glaucoma
another type of visual disability is

00:05:13.520 --> 00:05:17.039
colorblindness
and colorblindness affects eight percent

00:05:17.039 --> 00:05:21.919
of males
and half a percent of females

00:05:22.479 --> 00:05:26.560
types of color blindness include red
green color blindness

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:30.560
blue yellow and there's even different
types of each one

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:34.479
and then there's complete color
blindness

00:05:34.479 --> 00:05:38.800
some uses of color and contrast can
actually affect comprehension

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:43.919
either negatively or positively
especially for those with cognitive

00:05:43.919 --> 00:05:49.680
learning and neurological disabilities
now in the us there's 14.8 million

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:52.400
people
who have a cognitive disability

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:55.440
unfortunately i wasn't able to find a
worldwide number on that but

00:05:55.440 --> 00:05:58.800
as you can see these are not small
populations these are not small numbers

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:01.600
we're talking about

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:06.560
and here's another one i hear from
designers and developers my clients

00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:11.840
don't serve anyone with a disability
i actually hear this from clients too i

00:06:11.840 --> 00:06:14.720
mean you can't see who's coming to a
website you can't

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:18.639
see who's reading your electronic
documents you might only find out if

00:06:18.639 --> 00:06:20.880
somebody
complains that they can't get around the

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:24.080
site or they can't access content in a
brochure

00:06:24.080 --> 00:06:30.639
or they can't read something and they
might just go to a competitor instead

00:06:30.639 --> 00:06:33.759
the web content accessibility guidelines
called wik

00:06:33.759 --> 00:06:38.720
for short tell us how to be compliant
these are internationally accepted

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:41.919
guidelines and there are three levels of
conformance

00:06:41.919 --> 00:06:45.759
there's a double a and triple a and they
range from

00:06:45.759 --> 00:06:50.800
minimum to strict the typical level of
conformance to meet

00:06:50.800 --> 00:06:55.919
is double a triple a is a much
less common request so in my

00:06:55.919 --> 00:07:02.639
presentation i'm focusing on a
and double a and focusing on wiki 2.1

00:07:02.639 --> 00:07:07.680
one of the wicket guidelines that deals
with color is 1.4.1 use of color

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:11.919
which says the color cannot be the only
visual means

00:07:11.919 --> 00:07:15.199
of conveying information and that could
be

00:07:15.199 --> 00:07:20.160
text that could be social media icons
for example

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.440
it could be data graphics i mean in this
case

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:26.960
the pie chart is conveying data on each
piece of the pie

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:30.880
but it's also conveying information from
each piece of the pie

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:33.680
to the legend

00:07:33.919 --> 00:07:37.440
color alone also cannot be the only
visual means of indicating

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:44.080
an action here's an example where
color alone is being used to do that

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:47.280
cited users with or without a disability
would not be able to tell

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:52.000
that the word this is a hyperlink the
blue link text is hardly noticeable

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.560
against the surrounding
black body text i mean we could assume

00:07:56.560 --> 00:08:00.080
it's a hyperlink but that's if we even
notice the color difference at all

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:03.280
which most people won't

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:08.800
color alone cannot be the only visual
means of prompting a response

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:14.160
so for example a button
alone cannot be the only visual means of

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:18.800
distinguishing a visual element
that could be a form field border just

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:22.639
to show that it's a form-field border
and it could also be showing a field

00:08:22.639 --> 00:08:29.599
that contains an error as well
wik 1.4.3 contrast minimum

00:08:29.599 --> 00:08:34.399
says that text and images of text have a
contrast ratio of at least

00:08:34.399 --> 00:08:38.640
four and a half to one except for large
text

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:44.880
incidental elements and logos
normal text is defined as 14 points or

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:48.480
less
or 18.66 pixels if you're working on the

00:08:48.480 --> 00:08:51.440
web
or smaller than that and it needs to

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:54.240
meet a contrast ratio of four and a half
to one

00:08:54.240 --> 00:08:59.920
or more like i just mentioned but large
text is at least 14 points or 18.6

00:08:59.920 --> 00:09:04.880
pixels
and bold or at least 18 points or 24

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:09.200
pixels
in any weight typically

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:12.399
you're going to see normal sized text
used for

00:09:12.399 --> 00:09:16.320
body text and header and footer text
photo captions

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:20.240
block quotes navigation menus and
hyperlinks

00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:26.240
tables and form fields buttons
form instructions and error messages and

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:31.680
then large text will usually be used for
headings and sometimes block quotes and

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:36.880
buttons
to check contrast you simply enter the

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:41.519
hexadecimal codes for the foreground
and background colors into a contrast

00:09:41.519 --> 00:09:47.120
checker and in this example i'm using
the web aim contrast checker

00:09:47.120 --> 00:09:50.399
and then it will give you the contrast
ratio

00:09:50.399 --> 00:09:53.760
with this particular checker you could
even click the permalink

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:58.640
link under that and then copy the url
from it in case you want to show this

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:03.519
information to someone else
or refer back to it later

00:10:03.519 --> 00:10:09.839
wiki 1.4.11
non-text contrast says that user

00:10:09.839 --> 00:10:15.600
interface components and their states
such as focus and hover and so forth and

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:20.000
graphical images excuse me objects have
a contrast ratio

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.680
of at least three point three to one
against

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:28.320
adjacent colors and this applies to form
fields

00:10:28.320 --> 00:10:32.880
at their default and then at other
various states so it could be a field in

00:10:32.880 --> 00:10:38.720
keyboard focus and it could be social
media icons

00:10:38.800 --> 00:10:42.079
the web aim contrast checker also has a
section

00:10:42.079 --> 00:10:46.000
for graphical objects and user interface
components so it will tell you right

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:51.360
there if that's passed or failed
hyperlinks need to meet the same

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:54.480
requirements as text against their
background

00:10:54.480 --> 00:10:58.000
but if color alone and no additional
styling

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:03.600
such as an underline is being used then
hyperlinks will also need to have a

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:08.560
three to one contrast against the
surrounding text color

00:11:08.720 --> 00:11:11.920
the web aim contrast checker also has a
link

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:15.920
contrast checker where you enter the
hexadecimal codes for the link

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:19.600
and the body text and the background
colors and then it will tell you if

00:11:19.600 --> 00:11:22.880
they pass or fail

00:11:23.279 --> 00:11:31.360
now there are no contrast requirements
for logos images that are purely

00:11:31.360 --> 00:11:34.079
decorative
and those could be decorative borders

00:11:34.079 --> 00:11:40.320
they could be visual dividers
or icons that don't convey any meaning

00:11:40.399 --> 00:11:44.800
inactive user interface components such
as a button that doesn't become active

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:49.920
until someone fills out
all the required form fields

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.240
content that is not visible to anyone

00:11:54.399 --> 00:11:58.720
images that contain significant other
visual content so if you have

00:11:58.720 --> 00:12:04.399
text that's unimportant or just happens
to be in an image like this street sign

00:12:04.399 --> 00:12:08.320
in a photo that would not have to meet a
contrast requirement

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:12.079
unless in this particular case unless we
actually want to use this image to

00:12:12.079 --> 00:12:15.839
convey
south 2nd avenue but other examples

00:12:15.839 --> 00:12:18.959
would be
an image of a magazine article that's

00:12:18.959 --> 00:12:23.440
being used decoratively and not meant to
actually be read

00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:27.920
and heat maps which have to use low
contrast colors so that you can see the

00:12:27.920 --> 00:12:34.480
page content beneath the colors
and then screenshots besides checking

00:12:34.480 --> 00:12:37.360
contrast
we can check to see how something would

00:12:37.360 --> 00:12:42.639
look to someone with color blindness
we can check for this by using a color

00:12:42.639 --> 00:12:46.000
blindness simulator
and in this example i've used the

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:51.600
cobless color blindness simulator
and so i upload a pie chart

00:12:51.600 --> 00:12:54.880
and then the color blindness simulator
shows how

00:12:54.880 --> 00:12:58.800
this pie chart with those particular
colors would look to people with varying

00:12:58.800 --> 00:13:01.200
forms
of color blindness and you can see

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:07.839
there's quite a few types there

00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:14.959
so you can see how very different this
pie chart would appear to some people

00:13:14.959 --> 00:13:19.200
in some cases you could still make out
the differences in the legend

00:13:19.200 --> 00:13:23.279
but with some types of colorblindness
there isn't much of a difference between

00:13:23.279 --> 00:13:29.360
them visually so once we
find issues and we've checked for them

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:34.639
how do we resolve them
there's actually a few things we can do

00:13:34.639 --> 00:13:40.399
we can increase the contrast between the
foreground and background

00:13:40.480 --> 00:13:44.000
in this example we can darken the light
green

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:48.320
until it has sufficient contrast but the
change is really drastic

00:13:48.320 --> 00:13:52.959
and this might be undesirable in the
design i mean it would be for me

00:13:52.959 --> 00:13:56.399
it's actually from my own brand color
palette and it's too dark for my taste

00:13:56.399 --> 00:14:03.279
so and the look i'm trying to achieve
in this case darkening this particular

00:14:03.279 --> 00:14:05.760
orange from a client's brand color
palette

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:09.600
only slightly gives it sufficient
contrast and the change is hardly

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:12.240
noticeable

00:14:12.480 --> 00:14:16.399
here's an example of a hyperlink that
does not meet contrast requirements

00:14:16.399 --> 00:14:20.800
against the body text color
the link contrast checker assesses the

00:14:20.800 --> 00:14:24.560
hyperlink color
against the background and the body text

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:28.240
colors
now the link text is a different color

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:32.639
but it doesn't have enough contrast
to distinguish it from the body text so

00:14:32.639 --> 00:14:35.760
it's not obvious to some people that
it's a hyperlink

00:14:35.760 --> 00:14:40.399
in other words it's using color alone
not contrast and not styling

00:14:40.399 --> 00:14:46.079
to show that it's a hyperlink
now this particular blue is slightly

00:14:46.079 --> 00:14:50.000
lighter and it still meets the contra
contrast requirements against the

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:53.360
background and the body text
but it is still a best practice to

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:58.800
underline links or give them
a border bottom in the css

00:14:58.800 --> 00:15:04.480
another way to resolve contrast issues
is to use a completely different color

00:15:04.480 --> 00:15:07.920
here the white text on this orange
background of the button

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:12.160
does not meet contrast requirements and
so we have several options we can change

00:15:12.160 --> 00:15:15.600
the background color to the dark blue
from

00:15:15.600 --> 00:15:19.600
this is from my color palette and the
blue gives sufficient contrast against

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:23.120
the white
and then we could change the text to

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:26.079
that same blue
which has sufficient contrast against

00:15:26.079 --> 00:15:31.279
the orange as well
or we can even reverse those colors

00:15:31.279 --> 00:15:35.920
now here with these form field borders
the orange does not have enough contrast

00:15:35.920 --> 00:15:38.959
with the background instead of darkening
it though

00:15:38.959 --> 00:15:42.160
we could choose another color from the
brand color palette that does have

00:15:42.160 --> 00:15:47.839
sufficient contrast
in this example with social media icons

00:15:47.839 --> 00:15:51.040
these are really light so we could
choose another color

00:15:51.040 --> 00:15:56.959
from the client's color palette
now with some elements we can use

00:15:56.959 --> 00:16:02.480
styling to differentiate them
going back to the hyperlink example you

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:06.560
know if the link text has sufficient
contrast with the background

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:10.320
then instead of using contrast to
distinguish it from the surrounding body

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:13.360
text
we could simply add an underline or a

00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:19.120
border bottom style
or we can add a background color

00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:25.199
we could also add a background color to
show a field that is in focus

00:16:25.199 --> 00:16:30.079
to show form fields that have an error
we could use a thicker outline

00:16:30.079 --> 00:16:33.839
and or one that's in a different color
that has sufficient contrast with the

00:16:33.839 --> 00:16:38.639
background
and the field border default state

00:16:38.639 --> 00:16:42.160
so now let's talk about how the
accessibility of our color choices can

00:16:42.160 --> 00:16:44.880
affect branding
and why accessibility should be brought

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:49.360
up as early as possible even at the
branding stage

00:16:49.360 --> 00:16:52.639
number one is that the visual brand
integrity can

00:16:52.639 --> 00:16:59.279
be affected now here's an example
of that so this is the branding of my

00:16:59.279 --> 00:17:02.240
client
based business and it uses a light green

00:17:02.240 --> 00:17:06.880
and gray as the two main colors
purple is what i want to be more of an

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:09.839
accent color now i devel
developed these colors before i got into

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:12.880
accessibility and was even aware of
accessibility so

00:17:12.880 --> 00:17:16.880
this is all happening after the fact so
it would have to be a much different

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:22.000
darker hue of green as i showed earlier
like an army green and that would change

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.880
my brand color palette and the brighter
look that i want to have

00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:31.039
so you might also need to weigh whether
or not the design will end up being

00:17:31.039 --> 00:17:35.760
too heavy on one color which you know
you may not want so in this case

00:17:35.760 --> 00:17:39.360
in order to meet contrast requirements
in certain places i've had to change the

00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:43.679
gray to
purple now i don't care for having so

00:17:43.679 --> 00:17:46.799
much purple
it's more prominent than my primary

00:17:46.799 --> 00:17:51.360
brand colors
but it does give a warmer feel

00:17:51.360 --> 00:17:55.600
something to consider with your work is
how will brand recognition be affected

00:17:55.600 --> 00:17:58.880
if you end up needing to use more of the
secondary colors

00:17:58.880 --> 00:18:03.360
rather than the primary ones or having
to darken a client's primary color

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:06.640
palette
